y past, Vasil' Bykov and Iurii Bondarev write on war themes. Iurii Trifonov depicts the ordinary life of the city intelligentsia. Valentin Rasputin's stories are concerned with the fate of the Siberian peasant. Chingiz Aitmatov deals with problems of universal significance in a Kirghiz setting. This book recognizes the difficulties faced by contemporary creative writers in the USSR, and reflects the intellectual, ideological, and political atmosphere in which they work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aRussian fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757557140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487575571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487575571.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK